{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778549721,"nonce":"1Z+q4f3WLekHnhSGgBP3a1Z+vQA=","message":"**Correction to comment #18 (`c8909aa`) — lit-replication 6-cell matrix is a POSITIVE result, not a negative one.**\n\nThe earlier comment headlined `f47abb1` as a \"negative result for faithful C\u0026S Eq. 15 schedule\" on the strength of within/across pairwise RMSE ratios (no cell beating \u003c 0.5). That framing was wrong: the within/across ratio is the wrong primary metric for a training-method-variant matrix (no a priori reason for cells to produce similar trajectories, so nearest-across-cell RMSE just reflects cost-induced kinematic divergence between cells). Cross-cutting metric-pitfall lesson logged on `4d38c15`.\n\n**Corrected reading on absolute within-cell vel RMSE (m/s) + hold drift (mm) + peak vel (m/s):**\n\n| Cell | Vel within-RMSE | Hold drift | Peak vel |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| lit__flat_jerk | 0.1086 | 22.9 mm | 0.59 m/s |\n| lit__flat_nojerk | 0.0918 | 24.3 mm | 0.61 m/s |\n| lit__post_jerk | 0.0423 | 3.3 mm | 0.79 m/s |\n| lit__full_jerk | 0.0426 | 3.4 mm | 0.79 m/s |\n| **lit__post_nojerk** | **0.0361** | **2.34 mm** | **0.969 m/s** |\n| lit__full_nojerk | 0.0414 | 2.74 mm | 0.964 m/s |\n\n**Training-method takeaways for this coord:**\n\n1. **Powerlaw `(t/T)^6` + jerk-off is the strongest combination of the six.** Tightest within-cell clustering, lowest anticipation, fastest plausible peak velocity. `post_nojerk` edges `full_nojerk` on both clustering and drift.\n\n2. **What fails is the FLAT schedule, not lit-replication writ large.** The literature-faithful uniform-time target-switching cost (Shahbazi-style) gives catastrophic 23–24 mm anticipation and 2–3× worse within-cell clustering than either powerlaw variant. Earlier comment #18 framed this as \"C\u0026S Eq. 15 powerlaw does not reduce variance\" — actually powerlaw does its job; the prior matrix did not have the right primary metric to surface it.\n\n3. **Jerk regulariser is null at the corrected effective weight.** At `nn_hidden_derivative = 1e-3` (Shahbazi-effective), `nn_output_jerk = 1e5` does not improve within-cell clustering on any schedule (and marginally hurts on flat / post-go). Consistent with C\u0026S 2019 not using a jerk term. Earlier statement that \"jerk does not funnel replicates here\" stands, just no longer reads as a negative.\n\n4. **Residual 2–3 mm hold drift in the winning cells unambiguously triggers the conditional pre-go-mask follow-up matrix.** Filed as **`3702f54`** — sweep `--nn-output-pre-go ∈ {0, 1e-2, 1e-1, 1.0}` on top of `lit__post_nojerk` (and optionally `lit__full_nojerk`).\n\nDoc correction lives on branch `feature/f47abb1-ratio-correction` (auth request `388d6576`); explicit correction comment on `f47abb1`.","files":null}]}